  "texts": [
    "In the face of the complexity of the urban environment, the graph is constructed by considering urban elements as nodes of the graph and the connecting relationships between them as edges in the graph.",
    "This provides a new perspective for region representation learning.",
    "However, traditional GNNs are prone to the problem of excessive smoothing when dealing with large-scale graph data.",
    "To address this challenge, (Xu and Zhou 2407) proposed Coarsened Graph Attention Pooling (CGAP), which generates coarse-grained intermediate graphs with global feature representations by constructing a hierarchical graph pooling architecture and fusing local attention mechanisms.",
    "Moreover, CGAP also skillfully integrates region-specific attribute information (e.g., contextual environments and point-of-interest), which significantly enhances the characterization of urban regions and provides more accurate data support for urban management and planning."
  ],
